al deference, institutional arrangements, and strategic decision making by political elites in Ottawa and Washington. By bringing the insights of law and politics scholarship to bear on a subject matter traditionally addressed by international relations scholars, Krikorian shows that the classic division in political science between these two fields of study, though suitable in the postwar era, is outdated in the context of a globalized world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aForeign trade regulation -- Political aspects -- Canada. 0aForeign trade regulation -- Political aspects -- United States. 0aWorld Trade Organization. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482308140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774823081423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774823081/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles